<document><id>28604678</id><passage><infon key="type">title</infon><offset>0</offset><text>Dynamic subunit turnover in ESCRT-III assemblies is regulated by Vps4 to mediate membrane remodelling during cytokinesis.</text><annotation id="0"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">128866</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="28" length="9"/><text>ESCRT-III</text></annotation><annotation id="1"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">9525</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="65" length="4"/><text>Vps4</text></annotation></passage><passage><infon key="type">abstract</infon><offset>122</offset><text>The endosomal sorting complex required for transport (ESCRT)-III mediates membrane fission in fundamental cellular processes, including cytokinesis. ESCRT-III is thought to form persistent filaments that over time increase their curvature to constrict membranes. Unexpectedly, we found that ESCRT-III at the midbody of human cells rapidly turns over subunits with cytoplasmic pools while gradually forming larger assemblies. ESCRT-III turnover depended on the ATPase VPS4, which accumulated at the midbody simultaneously with ESCRT-III subunits, and was required for assembly of functional ESCRT-III structures. In vitro, the Vps2/Vps24 subunits of ESCRT-III formed side-by-side filaments with Snf7 and inhibited further polymerization, but the growth inhibition was alleviated by the addition of Vps4 and ATP. High-speed atomic force microscopy further revealed highly dynamic arrays of growing and shrinking ESCRT-III spirals in the presence of Vps4. Continuous ESCRT-III remodelling by subunit turnover might facilitate shape adaptions to variable membrane geometries, with broad implications for diverse cellular processes.</text><annotation id="2"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">27243,51652,128866</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="126" length="60"/><text>endosomal sorting complex required for transport (ESCRT)-III</text></annotation><annotation id="3"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">27243,51652,128866</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="271" length="9"/><text>ESCRT-III</text></annotation><annotation id="4"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">128866</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="413" length="9"/><text>ESCRT-III</text></annotation><annotation id="5"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">128866</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="547" length="9"/><text>ESCRT-III</text></annotation><annotation id="6"><infon key="code">222</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">27183,9525</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="582" length="6"/><text>ATPase</text></annotation><annotation id="7"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">9525</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="589" length="4"/><text>VPS4</text></annotation><annotation id="8"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">128866</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="648" length="9"/><text>ESCRT-III</text></annotation><annotation id="9"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">128866</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="712" length="9"/><text>ESCRT-III</text></annotation><annotation id="10"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">27243|6382</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="748" length="4"/><text>Vps2</text></annotation><annotation id="11"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">51652</infon><infon key="type">Gene</infon><location offset="753" length="5"/><text>Vps24</text></annotation><annotation id="12"><infon key="code">444</infon><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">128866</infon><infon key="type">GENERIF</infon><location offset="771" length="9"/><text>ESCRT-III</text></annotation><annotation id="13"><infon key="NCBI Gene identifier">